    <!-- AltGr explanation -->
    <section class="section pt-0">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <div class="alert alert--info">
          <p class="mb-2"><strong>Why do some conflicts exist?</strong></p>
          <p class="text-secondary">
            On Windows, <kbd>AltGr</kbd> sends <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd> to the system.
            Modern applications (Word, Excel, browsers) correctly tell the two apart.
            A few Java- or Electron-based apps confuse them,
            which can block certain AltGr characters.
            The solution is always the same: remap the conflicting shortcut.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Applications -->
    <section class="section border-top">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <div class="section__header">
          <h2 class="section__title">Applications</h2>
          <p class="section__subtitle">Click an application to see the conflicts and the fix.</p>
        </div>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >VS Code — 2 conflicts</summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <p class="mb-3">
              <strong>Fix:</strong> <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>K</kbd> <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>S</kbd>
              to open the shortcuts, then disable the conflicting entries.
              Or add an unbound entry in <code>keybindings.json</code>.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>[</kbd> blocks <code>[</code> (AltGr+J) — Jump to Matching Bracket</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>]</kbd> blocks <code>]</code> (AltGr+K) — Jump to Matching Bracket</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >JetBrains (IntelliJ, PyCharm, WebStorm) — 7 conflicts</summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <p class="mb-2">
              <strong>Fix:</strong> <code>Settings &gt; Keymap</code>,
              right-click the action &gt; <em>Remove Shortcut</em>.
            </p>
            <p class="mb-3 text-secondary">
              <strong>Tip:</strong> in the IntelliJ registry
              (<kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>A</kbd> &gt; <em>Registry</em>),
              disable <code>actionSystem.force.alt.gr</code> to fix all conflicts at once.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>N</kbd> blocks <code>~</code> (AltGr+N) — Inline Refactor</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>O</kbd> blocks <code>œ</code> (AltGr+O) — Optimize Imports</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> blocks <code>–</code> (AltGr+T) — Surround With</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>B</kbd> blocks <code>ß</code> (AltGr+B) — Go to Implementation</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>H</kbd> blocks <code>|</code> (AltGr+H) — Call Hierarchy</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>J</kbd> blocks <code>[</code> (AltGr+J) — Surround with Live Template</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>F</kbd> blocks <code>}</code> (AltGr+F) — Extract Field</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >Adobe Photoshop — 3 conflicts</summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <p class="mb-3">
              <strong>Fix:</strong> <code>Edit &gt; Keyboard Shortcuts</code>
              (<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>K</kbd>).
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>A</kbd> blocks <code>æ</code> (AltGr+A) — Select All Layers</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>W</kbd> blocks <code>«</code> (AltGr+W) — Close All</li>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>G</kbd> blocks <code>\</code> (AltGr+G) — Clipping Mask</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >Figma — 1 conflict <span class="compat-badge compat-badge--danger">not remappable</span></summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <ul class="mb-3">
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>G</kbd> blocks <code>\</code> (AltGr+G) — Frame Selection</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="alert alert--warning">
              <p class="text-secondary">
                <strong>Figma doesn't let you remap its shortcuts.</strong>
                Use the context menu (right-click) or temporarily switch
                to the standard AZERTY with <kbd>Win</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >Discord — 1 conflict</summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <p class="mb-3">
              <strong>Fix:</strong> <code>Settings &gt; Keybinds</code>,
              disable the relevant shortcut.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>A</kbd> blocks <code>æ</code> (AltGr+A) — Return to the active voice channel</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="compat-app">
          <summary >Slack — 1 conflict <span class="compat-badge compat-badge--danger">not remappable</span></summary>
          <div class="compat-app__body">
            <ul class="mb-3">
              <li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> blocks <code>–</code> (AltGr+T) — Comment thread (canvas)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="alert alert--warning">
              <p class="text-secondary">
                <strong>Slack's Canvas shortcuts aren't remappable.</strong>
                Temporarily switch with <kbd>Win</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Video games -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <div class="section__header">
          <h2 class="section__title">Video games</h2>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mb-3">The ² key (game console)</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary mb-3">
          AZERTY Global replaces <kbd>²</kbd> with <kbd>@</kbd> on the key to the left of <kbd>1</kbd>.
          The impact depends on how the game detects the console key:
        </p>
        <ul class="mb-4">
          <li class="text-secondary mb-2">
            <strong>By scancode</strong> (physical position): the console works normally.<br>
            ✅ Skyrim, Fallout 4, Counter-Strike 2, CS:GO.
          </li>
          <li class="text-secondary">
            <strong>By character</strong> (virtual key): the console may not open.<br>
            ⚠️ Older Source Engine games (Garry's Mod, TF2, Portal), some Unreal Engine and Unity games.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <div class="alert alert--warning mb-6">
          <p class="text-secondary">
            <strong>Solutions:</strong> rebind the console in the game's INI file,
            or switch to the standard AZERTY with <kbd>Win</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mb-3">Smart Caps Lock</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary mb-6">
          AZERTY Global's Caps Lock only affects letters.
          Games detect <strong>the key press</strong>, not the Caps Lock state:
          no known impact, including in MMOs and FPS games that rebind Caps Lock (WoW, Valorant).
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3">Anti-cheat</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary mb-4">
          Behavior depends on which Windows channel you use. Both options remain local
          and reversible, but they don't work the same way under the hood.
        </p>
        <div class="d-grid gap-4 mb-4">
          <div class="card">
            <h4 class="card__title">Classic EXE / MSKLC installer</h4>
            <p class="card__text">
              This channel installs a standard Windows keyboard layout, with no AZERTY Global
              application hook. It's the most neutral channel if you often play
              anti-cheat protected games.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h4 class="card__title">Microsoft Store app</h4>
            <p class="card__text">
              The app uses a local keyboard hook to remap keystrokes after
              sign-in. It never logs, stores or transmits any keystroke,
              doesn't inject a DLL into games, and voluntarily pauses itself on some
              anti-cheat protected games to reduce any ban risk.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted">
          If in doubt with a competitive game, use the classic installer or
          disable the Microsoft Store app with <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>Caps Lock</kbd>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

